---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Icon from "../components/Icon.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="About — Mein Scope"
  description="Mein Scope was built in Uganda, where unreliable connectivity is an everyday constraint, not an edge case. That shaped an offline-first, purpose-built app for endoscopy and colonoscopy."
>
  <section class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 pt-20 pb-16 text-center sm:pt-28">
    <span class="section-label">About</span>
    <h1 class="mt-4 text-4xl font-heading tracking-[-0.03em] text-balance text-ink-950 sm:text-5xl">
      Built where the internet isn't guaranteed
    </h1>
    <p class="mx-auto mt-5 max-w-xl text-lg text-ink-500 text-balance">
      Mein Scope started with a simple observation: clinical software keeps assuming a connection
      that not every clinic has.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 pb-24">
    <div class="space-y-10">
      <div>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-heading tracking-[-0.015em] text-ink-950">The problem we saw</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-ink-500">
          A lot of endoscopy and colonoscopy intake still runs on paper, disconnected phone
          photos, and manually assembled reports — not because clinics don't want better tools,
          but because the tools that exist assume constant connectivity and a general-purpose
          workflow that doesn't match this specific procedure.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-ink-500">
          We built Mein Scope out of Uganda, where unreliable connectivity is an everyday planning
          constraint, not an edge case. That constraint shaped the product from the start:
          offline-first wasn't a feature we added later, it's the foundation everything else is
          built on.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-heading tracking-[-0.015em] text-ink-950">What that means in practice</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-ink-500">
          Patient data lives on the device, not a server you have to reach first. The app installs
          directly from a browser — no app store review, no IT deployment project. And instead of
          trying to be a general EHR, Mein Scope is scoped narrowly to endoscopy and colonoscopy
          workflows, with ENT support planned next.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h2 class="text-xl font-heading tracking-[-0.015em] text-ink-950">Where we're headed</h2>
        <p class="mt-3 leading-relaxed text-ink-500">
          Mein Scope today runs on a single device with local storage and manual backup/restore.
          Multi-device sync and account-based billing are on the roadmap — we're building those
          deliberately, not rushing them ahead of getting the core clinical workflow right.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-14 text-center">
      <a href="/contact" class="btn-primary">
        See Where We're At
        <Icon name="arrow-right" class="size-4" />
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
